article.description: Minnesota's reserves helped lead the biggest comeback in franchise history Friday, with the Lynx erasing a 20-point second-half deficit in a 61-59 victory over the Phoenix Mercury.
article.headline: Reserves spark largest comeback in Lynx history
article.linkText: Lynx rally from 20-point deficit to edge Mercury
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Lynx are developing a
reputation as a team that won't quit.

Minnesota's reserves helped lead the biggest comeback in
franchise history Friday, with the Lynx erasing a 20-point
second-half deficit in a 61-59 victory over the Phoenix Mercury.

The Lynx have won three of their last four games, and trailed by
at least 10 in all three victories. On Friday, Minnesota closed the
game on a 26-4 run over the final 6½ minutes, thanks in part to
pressure defense and hot shooting from its backups.

"We cleared our bench and figured we'd go young, go aggressive
and get our players off the bench some minutes," said Lynx coach
Suzie McConnell Serio, whose reserves outscored the Mercury 30-4.

Amber Jacobs and Amanda Lassiter each hit a pair of 3-pointers
in the run, and Stacey Lovelace-Tolbert scored nine points,
including five straight in the final 15 seconds that completed the
Minnesota comeback.

But when the Lynx trailed 55-35 with less than seven minutes to
play, a victory was the last thing on the minds of the reserves who
entered the game.

"At the time, we just wanted to get in there, play hard, be
aggressive and see what happens," Lovelace-Tolbert said. "We
weren't really watching the score -- we were just trying to take
each possession one at a time."

Anna DeForge scored 25 points to lead the Mercury, who have lost
three straight and are 2-4 on their seven-game road trip.

"We just didn't finish this game tonight," DeForge said. "It
was completely unacceptable, and I am very embarrassed right now. I
don't know how we lost it in the second half, but we sure found a
way to."

Lovelace-Tolbert hit a 3-pointer with 13 seconds remaining to
cut the Phoenix lead to 59-58. Diana Taurasi then missed a pair of
free throws, and Lovelace-Tolbert hit two foul shots at the other
end to give the Lynx their first lead.

Taurasi then missed a short jump shot and Katie Smith, who led
Minnesota with 10 points, hit one of two free throws with 5.4
seconds left. Lassiter intercepted a pass to seal the victory for
Minnesota.

"Basketball is about runs and momentum," Phoenix coach Carrie
Graf said. "When a team makes a run at you and steals momentum, if
you're a good team, you can take it right back. In that regard,
this team has a ways to go."
